<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-intervals-c-major-scale" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>C Major Scale</title>

  <p>In C major, the interval pattern remains the same ascending and descending.</p>
  <p>All major scales have the same pattern of intervals, so any major scale can be built by using this same pattern.</p>
  <p>The C major scale notes are C, D, E, F, G, A, B, and C.</p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-c-major-scale-notation">
    <caption>C major scale notation on a musical staff (ascending and descending).</caption>
    <image>
      <latex-image>
        <![CDATA[
\begin{music}
  \nobarnumbers
  \setclef10
  \startextract
  \notes \qa c \qa d \qa e \qa f \qa g \qa h \qa i \qa j \qa i \qa h \qa g \qa f \qa e \qa d \qa c \en
  \endextract
\end{music}
        ]]>
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <figure xml:id="fig-intervals-c-major-scale-table">
    <caption>Examples of intervals with notation and semitone counts (C major scale).</caption>
    <image>
      <latex-image>
        <![CDATA[
\newcommand{\MusiC}[1]{\adjustbox{trim=145pt 0pt 140pt 0pt, valign=c}{%
  \begin{music}
    \nobarnumbers
    \setclef10
    \startextract
    \notes #1
    \endextract
  \end{music}}}

\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
  \hline
  Interval & Quality & Notes & On Staff & Number of Semitones & Count\\
  \hline
  Second & Major & C~-~D & \MusiC{\qa c \qa d \en} & 2 & 3\\
  \hline
  Second & Major & D~-~E & \MusiC{\qa d \qa e \en} & 2 & 3\\
  \hline
  Second & Minor & E~-~F & \MusiC{\qa e \qa f \en} & 1 & 2\\
  \hline
  Second & Major & F~-~G & \MusiC{\qa f \qa g \en} & 2 & 3\\
  \hline
  Second & Major & G~-~A & \MusiC{\qa g \qa h \en} & 2 & 3\\
  \hline
  Second & Major & A~-~B & \MusiC{\qa h \qa i \en} & 2 & 3\\
  \hline
  Second & Minor & B~-~C & \MusiC{\qa i \qa j \en} & 1 & 2\\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
        ]]>
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>

</section>
